The paleontologists tell us that a number of really big carnivore species existed in the Pleistocene during the last Ice Age but became extinct when humans arrived. This is probably not a coincidence. Europe got a new apex predator--our ancestors. All the other carnivores were in competition for very finite resources and very small niches in an extremely hostile environment. Dire wolves were real, along with sabertooth tigers, and several enormous bear species MUCH bigger than present-day polar bears or brown bears.

>fantasy games

That's new to me, but then I think of the Western fantasy genre as something with roots in old Western legends-- Völuspá, the Prose Edda, the Cycle of the Kings, the Matter of France, the Arthurian Cycle, the Nibelunglied, the stories of King Gralon of Ys, even Greek and Roman mythology. These are the myths--the memes, if you prefer--that underlie our shared culture. When we read them, they resonate with us because of our cultural connection to them. When I think of modern Western fantasy, it is stories built from these same bricks, these same mythic structures. Authors are influenced by them who've never read the Eddas or even the Golden Bough. It's why the Hero's Journey makes sense to us whether the hero is Odysseus or Luke Skywlaker. In Western fantasy, dinosaurs, dire wolves, flying saucers, muh Grrrl Powah, and muh multiculturalism need not apply, for obvious reasons.

Odd. If Wikipedia is an acceptable source, the typical adult male wolf is well under 100 pounds . at least in most of Western Europe and North America. Hunters have killed individual males weighing over 150 pounds in Alaska and Siberia but those individuals were extreme outliers. Wolves are big, but there are domestic dog breeds significantly bigger. A healthy male adult Cane Corso can get up to around 110 pounds Irish Wolfhound males can get well past 120. Great Danes can approach 200.

Of course all these big breed dogs are generally pretty unhealthy and tend to die at only six to eight years old, from bone cancers that are extremely rare in breeds that don't grow so big so fast, of heart attacks from moving all that mass around with a heart that's right at its limits. They're really pushing the maximum viable size for a canid body--at least with the current breeding stock. Depending on the source you read, dire wolves were about this size--significantly larger than extant wolf species in the present day, but they were not horse-sized, as they are sometimes portrayed. It is not known how long-lived they were, but there were claims in 2021 that a team from UCLA were able to reconstruct and sequence the dire wolf genome from fossil remains. Big awoos when?
